efine itself as an outsider community. Indie’s love affair with the cassette culminated in the mixtape, which advanced indie’s image as a gift economy. By telling the cassette’s long and winding history, Drew demonstrates that sharing cassettes became an acceptable and meaningful mode of communication that initiated rituals of independent music recording, re-recording, and gifting.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aAlternative rock musicxHistory and criticism. 0aAudiocassettes. 0aDissemination of musicxHistoryy20th century. 0aMixtapes. 0aSound recordingsxSocial aspects. 0aSoundxRecording and reproducing. 7aMUSIC / Recording & Reproduction.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDuke University Press Complete eBook-Package 2024z978311135689140uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781478027713?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781478027713423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781478027713/original  a978-3-11-135689-1  Duke University Press Complete eBook-Package 2024b2024  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aEBA_EMB  aGBV-deGruyter-alles